        "title": "Seven young talents presented with Chiguru Chinmaya Award in Kalaburagi",
        "content": "March 21, 2026e-Paper\nThe View From India\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tLooking at World Affairs from the Indian perspective.\nFirst Day First Show\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tNews and reviews from the world of cinema and streaming.\nToday's Cache\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tYour download of the top 5 technology stories of the day.\nScience For All\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tThe weekly newsletter from science writers takes the jargon out of science and puts the fun in!\nData Point\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tDecoding the headlines with facts, figures, and numbers\nHealth Matters\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tRamya Kannan writes to you on getting to good health, and staying there\nThe Hindu On Books\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tBooks of the week, reviews, excerpts, new titles and features.\nMarch 21, 2026e-Paper\nUpdated  - March 21, 2026 10:00 pm IST - KALABURAGI\nChiguru Chinmaya Awards being presented to seven young talents across different fields in Kalaburagi.\n                                          | Photo Credit: SPECIAL ARRANGEMENT\nDr. P.S. Shankar Prathisthan, in association with the Dakshina Kannada Sangha and Rotary Club, presented the prestigious Chiguru Chinmaya Awards to seven emerging talents in different fields of arts and others as part of the Ugadi celebrations in Kalaburagi on Friday.\nThe Chiguru Chinmaya award winners included sisters Shivani S. Appa, a budding Bharatanatyam dancer, Bhavani S. Appa, and Maheshwari S. Appa, both budding singers. Other winners of the Chiguru Chinmaya Award were Kumari Sanvi Sandeep, a budding exponent of fine arts, Pranav Satyampet, who is an expert in memorising and reciting the Vachanas of 12th century social reformer Mahatma Basaveshwara and other contemporary Sharanas, Koushik N. Mudabi, a young Hindustani vocalist who has won several district and State-level awards, and Happy Raj, an expert Judo exponent who has won several awards in the Judo competitions held at the State and national levels.\nAnother award winner, Rakshita Konded, who has won several awards and recognition in the rangoli competitions at the State and national level competitions, was given the award in absentia.\nThe award carries a memento and a cash award of ₹2,000 each. The award winners were felicitated by Dr. Shankar and other dignitaries, including noted sculptor Chandrasekhar Shilpi, a national-level award winner who inaugurated the award function.\nPublished - March 21, 2026 07:48 pm IST\nCopyright© 2026, THG PUBLISHING PVT LTD. or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved.\nBACK TO TOP\nTerms & conditions  |  Institutional Subscriber\nComments have to be in English, and in full sentences. They cannot be abusive or personal. Please abide by our community guidelines   for posting your comments.\nWe have migrated to a new commenting platform. If you are already a registered user of The Hindu and logged in, you may continue to engage with our articles. If you do not have an account please register and login to post comments. Users can access their older comments by logging into their accounts on Vuukle.",
